00:04:05.410 --> 00:04:09.910
than on external factors,"
end of that quote,

00:04:09.910 --> 00:04:13.530
and if you sense anything polemical
at all about that introduction

00:04:13.530 --> 00:04:15.630
or you're sensing some
of that is real.

00:04:15.630 --> 00:04:20.210
So my approach is not to sell
you facts or alternative facts

00:04:20.210 --> 00:04:24.670
about African music but
to find creative ways

00:04:24.670 --> 00:04:28.460
of supporting your
own exploration of it.

00:04:28.460 --> 00:04:33.290
I'm not seeking to do Africa
from scratch, complete with maps

00:04:33.290 --> 00:04:39.690 position:56%
and photos nor do I wish to peddle
Africa to its historical oppressors,

00:04:39.690 --> 00:04:44.850 position:56%
I aim or about to reach readers
who'd like to listen to Africa music

00:04:44.850 --> 00:04:47.060
and for whom a modest elaboration

00:04:47.060 --> 00:04:52.340
of its core features
might deepen appreciation.

00:04:52.340 --> 00:04:54.610
What do I mean by African music?

00:04:54.610 --> 00:04:58.580
African music is music conceived,
created and performed at least

00:04:58.580 --> 00:05:02.060
in the first instance
by African peoples.

00:05:02.060 --> 00:05:06.490
It includes vast repatries
of precolonial origins,

00:05:06.490 --> 00:05:08.640
we call that traditional music,

00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:12.400
others of more recent vintage
associated with a populist sphere,

00:05:12.400 --> 00:05:16.980
we call that popular music, and
still others produced in of mold

00:05:16.980 --> 00:05:20.440
of arts composed music art,
we call them art music.

00:05:20.440 --> 00:05:24.810
My book focuses on traditional
music but includes examples

00:05:24.810 --> 00:05:26.930
of popular and art music.

00:05:26.930 --> 00:05:30.820
So let me just start of by
playing you an example of the kind

00:05:30.820 --> 00:05:33.580
of traditional music
that I write about,

00:05:33.580 --> 00:05:37.490
this is a southern Ewe
dance called Agbadza.

00:05:43.510 --> 00:05:48.380
[ Music ]

00:05:48.380 --> 00:05:50.680
That's not Agbadza.

00:05:57.510 --> 00:06:27.560
[ Music ]

00:06:27.560 --> 00:06:30.100
Okay, this is going to be a very
long evening if you're just going

00:06:30.100 --> 00:06:35.460
to sit and not move in any way
to this music, it's impossible

00:06:35.460 --> 00:06:38.760
to just sit and listen quietly.

00:06:38.760 --> 00:06:42.320
Okay, so my book has 8 chapters
and I just want to start

00:06:42.320 --> 00:06:45.930
by saying a few words about each
of them so that you get a sense

00:06:45.930 --> 00:06:49.550
of the project as a whole,
after that I'll focus

00:06:49.550 --> 00:06:52.420
on the fourth chapter
which deals with rhythm.

00:06:52.420 --> 00:06:57.290
So chapter one, Music
And In Society,

00:06:57.290 --> 00:07:01.330
explores the uncommonly close
connection between music

00:07:01.330 --> 00:07:05.460
and society, reminding
us that music is a part

00:07:05.460 --> 00:07:10.040
of society not apart from it.

00:07:10.040 --> 00:07:14.810
I identified 3 important
occasions for musicmaking as work,

00:07:14.810 --> 00:07:16.970
ritual and entertainment.

00:07:16.970 --> 00:07:20.690 position:56%
I discussed the role of music in the
lifecycle with particular reference

00:07:20.690 --> 00:07:24.110
to death, and I end the chapter
with reflections of the nature

00:07:24.110 --> 00:07:28.230
of the relationship between musical
structure and social structure

00:07:28.230 --> 00:07:31.150
and in particular the
role of circles

00:07:31.150 --> 00:07:36.950
in various conceptualizations
of music's social attachments.

00:07:36.950 --> 00:07:42.280
Chapter 2 On Musical Instruments
acknowledges the incredible number

00:07:42.280 --> 00:07:46.570
of sound producing objects
found on the African continent.

00:07:46.570 --> 00:07:49.250
There's been a great deal of
research on musical instruments

00:07:49.250 --> 00:07:53.040
and since part of my aim in
the book is to introduce some

00:07:53.040 --> 00:07:57.880
of the scholarship as well I cite
a handful of writings by 18th

00:07:57.880 --> 00:08:00.950
and 19th century explorers.

00:08:00.950 --> 00:08:05.720
Now there's a famous classification
system devised by two Germans

00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:09.000
on the eve of the first war,
on Bostol [phonetics] and Zacks

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:12.360
which is a mainstay of
scholarship on African music.

00:08:12.360 --> 00:08:14.920
So it specifies, I don't know,
some of you might know it.

00:08:14.920 --> 00:08:18.510
It specifies things like aerophones
which are wind instruments,

00:08:18.510 --> 00:08:21.410
chordophones, string
instruments, idiophones,

00:08:21.410 --> 00:08:25.340
self sounding instruments
and membranophones drums.

00:08:25.340 --> 00:08:29.350
I reject this classification
system and suggest instead

00:08:29.350 --> 00:08:32.500
that we pay attention
to indigenous ideas

00:08:32.500 --> 00:08:36.350
about musical instruments
including their names

00:08:36.350 --> 00:08:38.660
and number of which onomatopoeic.

00:08:38.660 --> 00:08:44.410
It is better to say dum dum
than to say talking drum.

00:08:44.410 --> 00:08:49.390
The chapter ends with commentary on
individual instruments like voice,

00:08:49.390 --> 00:08:54.750
hand clap, drum and so on and
on ensembles especially those

00:08:54.750 --> 00:08:59.990
that cultivate heterogeneous
sound ideal.

00:08:59.990 --> 00:09:05.010
Chapter 3 which is my personal
favorite explores what I believe is

00:09:05.010 --> 00:09:10.560
a deep and profound relationship
between language and music.

00:09:10.560 --> 00:09:14.160
I suggest that you will get
a lot more out of listening

00:09:14.160 --> 00:09:19.920
to Africa music if you know African
languages or are at least alert

00:09:19.920 --> 00:09:25.870
to the imprints of language as
both sound and sense on music.

00:09:25.870 --> 00:09:29.910
The topic is huge so I
focus on just six subtopics.

00:09:29.910 --> 00:09:35.580
First the relationship between
speech tones and melody and this

00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:39.170
because as you know many
indigenous African languages are

00:09:39.170 --> 00:09:40.470
tone languages.

00:09:40.470 --> 00:09:45.290
Second, talking drums that
is rendering speech on drums

00:09:45.290 --> 00:09:48.910
or mimicking the rendition
of speech on drums,

00:09:48.910 --> 00:09:52.890
it's the second level pretend
talking drum if you like.

00:09:52.890 --> 00:09:57.560
Third song which is an amalgam
of word and tone and those

00:09:57.560 --> 00:10:00.630 position:56%
of you who'd think I'm old-fashioned
will find a discussion here

00:10:00.630 --> 00:10:06.160
of a hip life song by Omanhene
Pozo a Ghanaian rapper.

00:10:06.160 --> 00:10:09.720
Chapter, then the fourth
thing is meta-language

00:10:09.720 --> 00:10:12.630
which is language about language.

00:10:12.630 --> 00:10:17.210
The fifth is idiophones
or picture words,

00:10:17.210 --> 00:10:22.080
the Germans call it cloud's
builder, these are marked words

00:10:22.080 --> 00:10:26.910
that vividly depicts
sensory perception

00:10:26.910 --> 00:10:31.750
and it's a linguistic phenomenon
that has a musical dimension.

00:10:31.750 --> 00:10:38.060
And finally a certain linguistic
residue in performance sensibility,

00:10:38.060 --> 00:10:41.580
is one of those things where,
I think there's something there

00:10:41.580 --> 00:10:45.850
but I can't really nail it down and
so I put it there as a suggestion.

00:10:45.850 --> 00:10:49.090
Chapter four is about Rhythm
which I will return to,

00:10:49.090 --> 00:10:52.140 position:56%
chapter five makes a case for Melody

00:10:52.140 --> 00:10:57.600
because African music surprisingly
is not normally credited

00:10:57.600 --> 00:11:00.160
with great melodic imagination.

00:11:00.160 --> 00:11:05.090
One scholar says that "melody is
not one of the essential features

00:11:05.090 --> 00:11:08.870
of African traditional
music", while another,

00:11:08.870 --> 00:11:11.790
a very distinguished
one writes I quote

00:11:11.790 --> 00:11:16.730 position:56%
"rhythmic interest often compensates
for the absence of melody

00:11:16.730 --> 00:11:20.090
or the lack of melodic
sophistication",

00:11:20.090 --> 00:11:25.930
this is actually a textbook but I
will not mention the author's name.

00:11:25.930 --> 00:11:28.490
These claims ought
to be interrogated

00:11:28.490 --> 00:11:30.530
and not accepted on face value.

00:11:30.530 --> 00:11:35.850
So by way of a counter
assertion I analyze a few songs,

00:11:35.850 --> 00:11:41.830
an Akah entertainment song, a
lullaby [foreign language] a song

00:11:41.830 --> 00:11:46.850
by Fella, and an Ewe dirge to show
that if you approach melody as

00:11:46.850 --> 00:11:51.880
and meaningful utterance then the
idea that there're any deficits

00:11:51.880 --> 00:11:57.830
in Africa melodic imagination
becomes frankly unintelligible.

00:11:57.830 --> 00:12:02.970
Chapter six discusses form, another
of those domains was elaboration

00:12:02.970 --> 00:12:06.250
by African musicians has
not garnered much praise

00:12:06.250 --> 00:12:10.970
but all you have to do is pay
close attention to the ingenuity

00:12:10.970 --> 00:12:14.430
with which performers
deployed techniques like call

00:12:14.430 --> 00:12:20.450 position:56%
and response variation form and
even moments form to see how nuanced

00:12:20.450 --> 00:12:23.750
to this aspect of Africa
music can be.

00:12:23.750 --> 00:12:26.060
I end the chapter with a suggestion

00:12:26.060 --> 00:12:29.910
that many African forms
are strategically partial,

00:12:29.910 --> 00:12:36.400
that is to say they incorporate
holes HOLES not phantom WHOLES.

00:12:36.400 --> 00:12:43.060
You see if you have a music
that is implicated in society,

00:12:43.060 --> 00:12:47.590
it's traces will always require
completion outside the narrow

00:12:47.590 --> 00:12:51.000
confines of the music itself.

00:12:52.640 --> 00:12:56.880
Chapter 7 deals with harmony,
forms of simultaneous doing,

00:12:56.880 --> 00:13:00.680
singing together, playing
together and I explore varieties

00:13:00.680 --> 00:13:04.990 position:56%
of parallelism like singing in
parallel thirds or parallel fourths,

00:13:04.990 --> 00:13:09.100
parallel fifths in different
performing practices.

00:13:09.100 --> 00:13:13.010
I also touch on modality and
inevitably on the influence

00:13:13.010 --> 00:13:19.100
of European functional harmony,
mostly it's Handel and Mendelson.

00:13:20.600 --> 00:13:24.690
The book ends with a
chapter on Appropriation,

00:13:24.690 --> 00:13:27.800
we all know that African
music has gone global

00:13:27.800 --> 00:13:32.370
that it is regularly appropriated
by musicians around the world,

00:13:32.370 --> 00:13:35.770
musicians in the popular music
business as well as composes

00:13:35.770 --> 00:13:37.910
of art music like Steve
Rise [phonetics].

00:13:37.910 --> 00:13:45.430
What are the ethics and aesthetics
of such acts of appropriation?

00:13:45.430 --> 00:13:49.660
I suggest the terms in which
such questions might be answered

00:13:49.660 --> 00:13:51.960
and I conclude by acknowledging
the work

00:13:51.960 --> 00:13:55.480 position:56%
of Africa's own arts music composers

00:13:55.480 --> 00:13:58.830 position:56%
in this case two Nigerian
composers Joshua Ozoigbe [phonetics]

00:13:58.830 --> 00:14:01.240
and Fred O [phonetics].

00:14:01.240 --> 00:14:06.120
So these are some of the topics
covered in the African imagination

00:14:06.120 --> 00:14:12.540
in music for a mere $27.95
you can explore them further

00:14:12.540 --> 00:14:15.440
if you are so inclined.

00:14:15.440 --> 00:14:18.670
So let me turn now to my main
task this evening which is to talk

00:14:18.670 --> 00:14:23.760 position:56%
about rhythm, I'm going to read you
parts of the four, play you a number

00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:30.520
of recorded examples, and then we
can have a discussion afterwards.

00:14:30.520 --> 00:14:34.610
So the Rhythmic Imagination
In African Music.

00:14:34.610 --> 00:14:38.420
By common consent rhythm
is the distinctive element

00:14:38.420 --> 00:14:43.920
in African music, "if European
music is specially marked

00:14:43.920 --> 00:14:48.020
by the rich variety of its forms
and the splendor of its harmonies,

00:14:48.020 --> 00:14:52.340
African music is similarly marked
by the fascination of its rhythms,

00:14:52.340 --> 00:14:55.330
Africans have not merely
cultivated their sense

00:14:55.330 --> 00:14:59.390
of rhythm far beyond ours
but must have started

00:14:59.390 --> 00:15:01.570
with a superior sense of rhythm".

00:15:01.570 --> 00:15:04.620
This has to be a British
writer, right?

00:15:04.620 --> 00:15:10.750
"says WF Ward" Here's one from
[inaudible] who's well known

00:15:10.750 --> 00:15:16.100
as a conductor, scholar of jazz
composer and so on "in respect

00:15:16.100 --> 00:15:20.820
to rhythm, African music is
unquestionably the world's most

00:15:20.820 --> 00:15:22.210
complex music."

00:15:22.210 --> 00:15:28.170
And finally here's a colorful
one from a book review,

00:15:28.170 --> 00:15:32.810
the book is A.M Jones's magnum
opus, it's a book called Studies

00:15:32.810 --> 00:15:36.250
in Africa Music it's from
1959, it's a newer book by now.

00:15:36.250 --> 00:15:40.570
The review is by a chap who was
actually a missionary to Nigeria

00:15:40.570 --> 00:15:47.610
in the 1950s and 60s
"Jones's book introduces us

00:15:47.610 --> 00:15:53.160
into a strange enchanted world of
pure sound made up almost entirely

00:15:53.160 --> 00:15:57.610
of complex patterns
of drum and gong taps

00:15:57.610 --> 00:16:01.630
to call these complex is an
understatement, the very thought

00:16:01.630 --> 00:16:05.950
of them makes one dizzy, imagine
two drummers playing together

00:16:05.950 --> 00:16:10.140 position:56%
and cross rhythm, three against two,
now stagger them so that they're

00:16:10.140 --> 00:16:13.870
out of phase, now add two
other drummers and a singer

00:16:13.870 --> 00:16:18.010
and clap accompliments all
rhythmically at cross purposes

00:16:18.010 --> 00:16:21.470
and out of phase with one another.

00:16:21.470 --> 00:16:25.290
And I was actually tempted to
play you that Agbadza example

00:16:25.290 --> 00:16:28.760
but that's the kind of thing
that he was thinking about.

00:16:28.760 --> 00:16:32.500
So now the reviewer's dual
invocation of the mystical

00:16:32.500 --> 00:16:37.170
and the technical, the mystical
being a strange enchanted world

00:16:37.170 --> 00:16:40.590
of pure sound and the
technical being three

00:16:40.590 --> 00:16:46.990 position:56%
against two cross rhythm, this dual
invocation I would say book ends the

00:16:46.990 --> 00:16:51.850
thematic content of the larger
discourse on African rhythm

00:16:51.850 --> 00:16:55.440 position:56%
and there're many stages in between.

00:16:55.440 --> 00:16:57.810
If you want more of
these quotations,

00:16:57.810 --> 00:17:01.700 position:56%
they're kind of entertaining you
can look them up in my earlier book,

00:17:01.700 --> 00:17:06.810 position:56%
the one called Representing
African Music which David mentioned.

00:17:06.810 --> 00:17:10.400
Now despite such wide
widespread affirmation,

00:17:10.400 --> 00:17:15.980
rhythm remains a contested topic
in African musical research, why?

00:17:15.980 --> 00:17:21.310 position:56%
Well, for one thing scholars bring a
variety of disciplinary backgrounds

00:17:21.310 --> 00:17:25.600 position:56%
so psychology, aesthetics, religion,
phenomenalogy, mathematics,

00:17:25.600 --> 00:17:29.440
music theory, musicology,
ethnomusicology and so on.

00:17:29.440 --> 00:17:32.880
While this could in
principle be enriching,

00:17:32.880 --> 00:17:36.530
it has also spawned a
proliferation of terminology

00:17:36.530 --> 00:17:40.350
that does not always promote good
understanding, we encounter temps

00:17:40.350 --> 00:17:44.700
like metrical inversion,
conmetric accents as opposed

00:17:44.700 --> 00:17:50.690
to contra metric accents, poly
meter, multimeter, African 44,

00:17:50.690 --> 00:17:54.040
simultaneous multidimensionality
and so I like that one

00:17:54.040 --> 00:17:56.350 position:56%
because there are so many syllables.

00:17:56.350 --> 00:18:01.170
There is an unproductive
excess here, I think.

00:18:01.170 --> 00:18:04.670
Second, scholars disagree
about the nature

00:18:04.670 --> 00:18:08.590
of the actual organizing principles
and how best to represent them,

00:18:08.590 --> 00:18:13.620 position:56%
is there a pulse of the beats and
