metrical colonization.

00:59:06.530 --> 00:59:10.450
There is an overall
change away from subtlety

00:59:10.450 --> 00:59:14.510
and a hierarchized
multiplicity to overtness

00:59:14.510 --> 00:59:18.080
and singularity, hegemony
if you like.

00:59:18.080 --> 00:59:25.460
The winks and knowing smiles
had gone, on difference.

00:59:25.460 --> 00:59:27.850
So although African music
has often been portrayed

00:59:27.850 --> 00:59:31.620
as being radically different
from Western music based

00:59:31.620 --> 00:59:36.350 position:56%
on an entirely different principles,
Horn Bussell wrote in 1928,

00:59:36.350 --> 00:59:40.030 position:56%
and more recently one of her
colleagues down in the South, wrote,

00:59:40.030 --> 00:59:44.220
"A different way of
being in the world."

00:59:44.220 --> 00:59:48.160 position:56%
There is essentially, that is to say
at a certain level of abstraction,

00:59:48.160 --> 00:59:52.910 position:56%
no difference between the organizing
principles of African rhythm

00:59:52.910 --> 00:59:55.010
and those of Western rhythm,

00:59:55.010 --> 01:00:00.670
both sets of repertories features
speech rhythms, a palpable tactics,

01:00:00.670 --> 01:00:03.860
symmetrical as well as
asymmetrical rhythmic phrases,

01:00:03.860 --> 01:00:05.990
superior beats and groups of beats.

01:00:05.990 --> 01:00:09.240
Periodicity is governed
by processes distributed

01:00:09.240 --> 01:00:13.960
across multiple dimensions, degrees
of polyrhythm, and the interplay

01:00:13.960 --> 01:00:17.050
between pre-composed
and improvised material.

01:00:17.050 --> 01:00:22.850
African rhythm indeed manifests the
same kind of hierarchic patterning

01:00:22.850 --> 01:00:24.950
that one finds in Western music.

01:00:24.950 --> 01:00:31.090
Namely, an elaborate surface held
in place by a simpler subsurface,

01:00:31.090 --> 01:00:35.090
a foreground subtending
a background.

01:00:35.090 --> 01:00:39.380
What differences there
are, stem from idiomatic

01:00:39.380 --> 01:00:43.400
and aesthetic choices made
by individual communities

01:00:43.400 --> 01:00:45.350 position:56%
for particular genres and locations.

01:00:45.350 --> 01:00:51.210
For example, it is not that Western
music lacks offbeat patterns,

01:00:51.210 --> 01:00:53.920
if you know Beethoven you
know that cannot be true.

01:00:53.920 --> 01:00:56.340
It is rather that some
African music,

01:00:56.340 --> 01:01:00.340
especially drum-base repertoires
that have acquired symbolic status

01:01:00.340 --> 01:01:04.900
as exemplars of authentic
African music, invests heavily

01:01:04.900 --> 01:01:08.030
in persistent offbeat patterning.

01:01:08.030 --> 01:01:11.850
It is not that African
music lacks down beats,

01:01:11.850 --> 01:01:16.230 position:56%
it is rather that some African music
takes the weight off the down beats

01:01:16.230 --> 01:01:19.820
in order to create a more
fluid or mobile process.

01:01:19.820 --> 01:01:23.670
It is not that Western instrumental
music is not the dependent

01:01:23.670 --> 01:01:28.010
on language, it is rather that the
speech mode in instrumental music

01:01:28.010 --> 01:01:29.580
of the 18th and the 19th centuries

01:01:29.580 --> 01:01:32.650
for example has been obscured
I think in the writings

01:01:32.650 --> 01:01:36.270 position:56%
of theorists with different agendas.

01:01:36.270 --> 01:01:39.090
Comparisons like these
can seem nave

01:01:39.090 --> 01:01:43.380
or counterintuitive especially
for people for whom the sound

01:01:43.380 --> 01:01:49.270
of African music is self-evidently
different from that of Western,

01:01:49.270 --> 01:01:51.050
but peering beneath the surface

01:01:51.050 --> 01:01:54.620
to behold the specific
organizational procedures,

01:01:54.620 --> 01:01:59.970
will reveal a significant degree
of subsurface convergence.

01:01:59.970 --> 01:02:05.730
Western and African rhythm share
patterns of well-formedness.

01:02:05.730 --> 01:02:10.450
It is in thematizing than
well-formed that preferences,

01:02:10.450 --> 01:02:14.420
