&gt;&gt; One last question.

01:31:01.880 --> 01:31:04.970
&gt;&gt; I just want to follow
up on a couple

01:31:04.970 --> 01:31:08.410
of questions that have been asked.

01:31:08.410 --> 01:31:15.100
I take issue with the maybe the
slightly negative connotation

01:31:15.100 --> 01:31:19.500
of the Herbie Hancock
appropriation just personally;

01:31:19.500 --> 01:31:24.860
I'm not make an argument but...

01:31:24.860 --> 01:31:28.980
I see maybe it's an homage that
takes us from the starting point,

01:31:28.980 --> 01:31:32.880
just something new with it,
but my question to you is,

01:31:32.880 --> 01:31:47.310
in your perspective, how should one
best take this African polyrhythmic

01:31:47.310 --> 01:31:52.940
heritage and create with
it while still honoring it?

01:31:52.940 --> 01:31:55.260
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I wish I have the
answer to that question.

01:31:55.260 --> 01:31:59.800
I did write a whole chapter on
appropriation and at one point,

01:31:59.800 --> 01:32:04.270
I said maybe the question of
appropriation is moot and it's moot

01:32:04.270 --> 01:32:09.510
after all because we are all, if
you like trapped into these sort

01:32:09.510 --> 01:32:14.760 position:56%
of inter-textual spaces you know, to
compose is to recompose, you know,

01:32:14.760 --> 01:32:17.700
how are you going to stand outside
the things that you remember,

01:32:17.700 --> 01:32:22.410 position:56%
the things that you know you
learned, and so on, in order to say,

01:32:22.410 --> 01:32:27.490
okay this is mine but this
one is not mine and so on.

01:32:27.490 --> 01:32:30.320
So I think there's
something very problematic

01:32:30.320 --> 01:32:33.400
about the idea of appropriation.

01:32:33.400 --> 01:32:37.390
However, there are degrees of
appropriation but that's one thing.

01:32:37.390 --> 01:32:40.770 position:56%
There are traditions that are based
on, somebody asked me about sampling

01:32:40.770 --> 01:32:45.600 position:56%
for example, where the compositional
method actually is premised

01:32:45.600 --> 01:32:47.920
on sampling things, you know.

01:32:47.920 --> 01:32:53.330
A lot of the hip life now that we
find coming out of Ghana, you know,

01:32:53.330 --> 01:32:56.710
these kids are sampling old you
know, like supposal that example

01:32:56.710 --> 01:32:59.230
that I mentioned so
there is old highlife

01:32:59.230 --> 01:33:02.830
and then there's what I'm doing
now which is all those rap stuff,

01:33:02.830 --> 01:33:09.690
we're bringing old and new together
and so on in this overt sampling

01:33:09.690 --> 01:33:12.480
if you like, in this
overt appropriation.

01:33:12.480 --> 01:33:17.320
I do think that there are
some political sides to this

01:33:17.320 --> 01:33:24.410
that my task really was to air the
issues and then let people talk

01:33:24.410 --> 01:33:26.180
about things from you know,

01:33:26.180 --> 01:33:30.150
whichever angle they
find appropriate.

01:33:30.150 --> 01:33:34.180
So for example, Steve Reich, a lot
of people talk about Steve Reich

01:33:34.180 --> 01:33:38.360
because as you know, he had a deep
interest not only in African music

01:33:38.360 --> 01:33:42.870
by the way, in Indonesian music,
in Indian music but he you know,

01:33:42.870 --> 01:33:47.270
went to Ghana in 1970 or
thereabout, studied some music,

01:33:47.270 --> 01:33:49.280
actually most of that time,
I think he had malaria

01:33:49.280 --> 01:33:52.230 position:56%
so he was ill [laughs] but you know,

01:33:52.230 --> 01:33:54.350
we have ways of dealing
with these people.

01:33:54.350 --> 01:34:00.410
But his work is influenced
by African music.

01:34:00.410 --> 01:34:03.700 position:56%
Sometimes they are of a quotational
sort, you know, so taking a timeline

01:34:03.700 --> 01:34:10.520
like in clapping music or you
know, I don't know, there you know,

01:34:10.520 --> 01:34:13.940
and he said, "What I wanted
to do was to think African

01:34:13.940 --> 01:34:16.280
but not to sound African."

01:34:16.280 --> 01:34:21.610
To think African, that is you know,
to internalize that way of thinking

01:34:21.610 --> 01:34:24.120 position:56%
but to speak my own musical language

01:34:24.120 --> 01:34:26.480
because he said that's
what he wanted to do.

01:34:26.480 --> 01:34:27.780
You know, composers say all kinds

01:34:27.780 --> 01:34:30.050
of interesting things,
sometimes very poetic.

01:34:30.050 --> 01:34:32.490
I don't know how you are able

01:34:32.490 --> 01:34:36.810
to finally test whether he achieved
his aim and so on, you know,

01:34:36.810 --> 01:34:39.350
but that's not for me to say.

01:34:39.350 --> 01:34:44.560
Ligeti is another one,
interesting case where in the book,

01:34:44.560 --> 01:34:47.750
Martin Scherzinger whom you
mentioned has actually done some

01:34:47.750 --> 01:34:49.050
interesting work on this.

01:34:49.050 --> 01:34:52.210
He actually went and spent
some time in Basel looking

01:34:52.210 --> 01:34:58.190
at Ligeti's sketches and he found
that you know, how you know,

01:34:58.190 --> 01:35:01.230
people keep like shopping
this on their sketch

01:35:01.230 --> 01:35:02.530
in the corners and so on.

01:35:02.530 --> 01:35:07.260
Ligeti had all of the stuff that he
was reading from various journals

01:35:07.260 --> 01:35:10.610
on African music, he was
fascinated by this stuff.

01:35:10.610 --> 01:35:13.270
Does Ligeti's music sound African?

01:35:13.270 --> 01:35:16.690
Not to my ears, I've
never heard anything

01:35:16.690 --> 01:35:20.330
that I would say it's conformative
with the repertoires that I know,

01:35:20.330 --> 01:35:24.760
you know, he had a deep interest,
he pursued it but in the end,

01:35:24.760 --> 01:35:26.060
all of this was if you like,

01:35:26.060 --> 01:35:30.530
domesticated within his
particular idiolect, you know.

01:35:30.530 --> 01:35:33.410
I think Scherzinger in writing

01:35:33.410 --> 01:35:37.030
that article thought he was
exposing Ligeti in a way,

01:35:37.030 --> 01:35:38.550
you know he doesn't
quite put it as crudely,

01:35:38.550 --> 01:35:42.480
he's a very sophisticated
thinker, but for us, you know,

01:35:42.480 --> 01:35:44.420
who are not as sophisticated,

01:35:44.420 --> 01:35:46.970
we see him saying you
see you thought this is

01:35:46.970 --> 01:35:50.280
like your avant-garde and pulls
up but let me show you how much

01:35:50.280 --> 01:35:54.500 position:56%
of a debt to Africa there is and
it's not on the surface of the music

01:35:54.500 --> 01:35:56.340
but we have to go and
look at these sketches,

01:35:56.340 --> 01:36:01.870
these private biographical
note in order to expose this.

01:36:01.870 --> 01:36:05.310 position:56%
When all of that is done, you know,
whatever you read, whether you stood

01:36:05.310 --> 01:36:08.350
on your head three times before you
wrote this with journals you read

01:36:08.350 --> 01:36:12.280
and so on, you write a piece
and people decide they like it

01:36:12.280 --> 01:36:13.930
or they don't like it, you know.

01:36:13.930 --> 01:36:21.010 position:56%
So really, it would be inappropriate
for one thing for me or I think

01:36:21.010 --> 01:36:25.690
for maybe, well, certainly for me,
to be offering any prescriptions

01:36:25.690 --> 01:36:28.420
about how you deal
with these things.

01:36:28.420 --> 01:36:32.790
I do think however that, a good
understanding of the phenomenon

01:36:32.790 --> 01:36:37.230
so a good understanding of
polyrhythmic to me is useful,

01:36:37.230 --> 01:36:39.490
and what you do with it
if you're a composer.

01:36:39.490 --> 01:36:43.740
Are you a composer?

01:36:43.740 --> 01:36:45.040
&gt;&gt; Oh no.

01:36:45.040 --> 01:36:46.340
&gt;&gt; Okay.

01:36:46.340 --> 01:36:48.830
&gt;&gt; I'm a drummer, player...

01:36:48.830 --> 01:36:53.670
&gt;&gt; Yeah, because you got the
metrical thing in the Hindehwu,

01:36:53.670 --> 01:36:56.300
which is good, very impressive.

01:36:56.300 --> 01:36:59.050
Anyway, so yeah that's, I mean,
I've gone on at length but that's

01:36:59.050 --> 01:37:03.010
where I'm coming so the chapter
on appropriation is not you know,

01:37:03.010 --> 01:37:05.050
pointing fingers at these bad guys.

01:37:05.050 --> 01:37:08.670
There is a piece by David Fanshawe
which some of you may have heard,

01:37:08.670 --> 01:37:13.760
maybe it was done in high schools
in a song called African Sanctus.

01:37:13.760 --> 01:37:20.840
It's a piece from the 70s and the
Kyrie of that piece has a call

01:37:20.840 --> 01:37:24.540
to prayer, an Arabic call to
prayer and then there's a sort

01:37:24.540 --> 01:37:29.270
of renaissance-type polyphony that
he composes on top of it, you know.

01:37:29.270 --> 01:37:31.800
If you read what the composer
says, he says I'm trying

01:37:31.800 --> 01:37:33.410
to bring together these two faiths.

01:37:33.410 --> 01:37:35.820
I'm trying to show that the
Christian faith you know,

01:37:35.820 --> 01:37:40.490
and the Muslim faith
you know, can coexist.

01:37:40.490 --> 01:37:44.900
That's his idealization
but if you're, you know,

01:37:44.900 --> 01:37:48.170
a kind of mischievous
hermeneuticist and you want

01:37:48.170 --> 01:37:51.700
to read this thing closely,
it's not so straightforward

01:37:51.700 --> 01:37:55.980
because somebody starts, somebody
finishes, so how do you determine

01:37:55.980 --> 01:37:58.680
who gets the first word
and who gets the last word?

01:37:58.680 --> 01:38:06.250
Why is the Arabic call to prayer
represented by a recording?

01:38:06.250 --> 01:38:07.820
So no presence, right?

01:38:07.820 --> 01:38:09.620
It's always done with a recording.

01:38:09.620 --> 01:38:13.060
[ Background conversation ]

01:38:13.060 --> 01:38:15.450
Very good, yeah.

01:38:15.450 --> 01:38:23.360
On his own original
recordings, this is what he does.

01:38:23.360 --> 01:38:28.270 position:56%
And you know, and then you can go on
and sort of worry this as you know,

01:38:28.270 --> 01:38:32.730 position:56%
unemployed, most colleges want to do
hermeneutics, we'll have a lot read

01:38:32.730 --> 01:38:34.220
but that's the beauty of music.

01:38:34.220 --> 01:38:36.760
It makes possible these sorts

01:38:36.760 --> 01:38:40.810
of call them idle you
know, speculations.

01:38:40.810 --> 01:38:47.900 position:56%
you know, it's a feel-good thing but
I think we should just sort of open

01:38:47.900 --> 01:38:50.990
out those issues and as I say,

01:38:50.990 --> 01:38:55.480
if one has a secure understanding
whether it's with the language,

01:38:55.480 --> 01:38:59.190
which Martha was asking
me about or whether it's

01:38:59.190 --> 01:39:02.120
of the rhythmic principles
that are at work,

01:39:02.120 --> 01:39:03.460
that's the way they are, yeah.

